<bibRefCitation author="Bousquet Y &amp; Laplante S." box="[282,617,1657,1684]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" refId="ref6681" refString="Bousquet Y, Laplante S. 2006. The insects and arachnids of Canada, part 24, Coleoptera: Histeridae. NCR Research Press; Ottawa, ON. 485 p." type="book" year="2006">Bousquet and Laplante (2006)</bibRefCitation>
list collections from tree hollows and cow manure. I have examined specimens collected in those habitats as well as wood chips, rodent (woodchuck and 
<taxonomicName box="[1062,1199,1691,1717]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Neotoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1062,1162,1691,1716]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Neotoma</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
) nests, horse manure, stable sweepings, Berlese of flood debris, and in Lindgren funnel traps.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[192,1441,1766,1927]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,303,1766,1792]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[309,547,1766,1791]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Xestipyge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conjunctum">
<emphasis box="[309,547,1766,1791]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Xestipyge conjunctum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[689,845,1766,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Xestipyge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geminatum">
<emphasis box="[689,707,1766,1791]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">X</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[720,845,1766,1791]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">geminatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and is mostly sympatric with that species; characters to differentiate those two species are given under 
<taxonomicName box="[740,896,1800,1826]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Xestipyge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geminatum">
<emphasis box="[740,758,1800,1825]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">X</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[771,896,1800,1825]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">geminatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. On first appearance 
<taxonomicName box="[1133,1293,1800,1826]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Xestipyge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conjunctum">
<emphasis box="[1133,1151,1800,1825]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">X</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1163,1293,1800,1825]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">conjunctum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is even more similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Warner" authorityYear="2021" box="[309,417,1833,1859]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Xestipyge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="skelleyi">
<emphasis box="[309,326,1834,1859]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">X</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[339,417,1833,1859]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">skelleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but specimens of the latter are easily differentiated by their western distribution, (usually) complete (to arch) elytral sutural stria, much more elongate tegmen in males, and lack of any indication of an incised chevron on pygidium in females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
